  <title>Description</title>
  <titlealts>
    <searchtitle>NHS Business Definition: Newborn Blood Spot Test - Description</searchtitle>
  </titlealts>
  <body>

  <p>
A 
    <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
            keyref="business_definition_newborn_blood_spot_test">Newborn Blood Spot Test</xref>
 is a 
    <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
            keyref="business_definition_clinical_investigation">Clinical Investigation</xref>
.  </p>
  <p>
A 
    <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
            keyref="business_definition_newborn_blood_spot_test">Newborn Blood Spot Test</xref>
 is performed to identify any serious condition that a baby may have. It involves the collection of a blood sample from the heel, usually when the baby is between 5 and 8 days of age.   </p>
  <p>All babies are screened for:</p>
  <ul>
      <li>
         <div>
            <p>Phenylketonuria</p>
         </div>
      </li>
      <li>
         <div>
            <p>Congenital Hypothyroidism</p>
         </div>
      </li>
      <li>
         <div>
            <p>Sickle Cell Disorders</p>
         </div>
      </li>
      <li>
         <div>
            <p>Cystic Fibrosis</p>
         </div>
      </li>
      <li>
         <div>
            <p>Medium Chain Acyl-CoA Dehydrogenase Deficiency (MCADD)</p>
         </div>
      </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
For further information on 
    <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
            keyref="business_definition_newborn_blood_spot_test">Newborn Blood Spot Tests</xref>
, see the NHS website at: 
    <xref href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/pregnancy-and-baby/newborn-blood-spot-test/"
            scope="external"
            format="html">Newborn blood spot test</xref>
.  </p>

